			<h1>HOW THE COURSE WORKS</h1>
		</div>
		<div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
			<p class="right_msg">
			<b>How does a week of Online UWC classes work?</b><br />
			There are three main elements that make Online UWC courses different. Every week we look at a different topic, but the rhythm of the class stays the same. On Friday before the week starts you receive an email with detailed class schedule and your assignments (this may require some reading, watching, research, writing, creativity and critical thinking). On Wednesday, around 6pm in your time zone, we organize a live Hangout on Air with the expert, where you have a chance to ask all of your questions. On Thursday, also around 6pm in your time zone you have the opportunity to speak to your classmates in a smaller group (with 5-10 students, depending on participation). Depending on the week, you may also be given additional assignments, which will give you a chance to meet in person students from a different region.
			<br /><br />
			<b>What makes Online UWC courses different?</b><br />
			We believe in student led education. This means that you are responsible for your own learning. You will be asked to lead group discussions and create your own community projects. We provide you with suggestions about things that we find interesting as part of our curriculum. However, you are always encouraged to find your own reading resources and guide your own direction of research. We assign homework prompts, but we give you complete freedom of how to complete them. As previous homeworks we have received infographics, videos, and yes, also songs and poems. Also, we’re not a typical online class, because you will actually be meeting to people and talking to them in live hangouts. It’s a really fun way to learn!
			<br /><br />
			<b>What is the time commitment?</b><br />
			The time commitment for you as a student of Online UWC is around 3-6 hours a week. There is a 1 hour video lecture each week and 1-2 hours of group discussion and assignment time. On top of this you have pre-class readings and many students choose to spend more time working on assignments with their fellow students.

					<br />
					<br />

			</p>
